*Ready Or Not - Release Trailer*

In 2023, the Irish indie studio [Void Interactive](https://voidinteractive.net/) published its first title, *Ready Or Not*, a tactical first-person shooter combined with a [police procedural](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Police_procedural), on Steam. The game has received praise for its attention to detail and realism. The developers consulted with real law enforcement agencies to ensure that scenarios and procedures were as realistic as possible. Everything from weapons, to NPC interactions and the damage system is rooted in reality, and incredibly detailed. On the other hand, the game has drawn a great degree of criticism for its adherence to realism, including [realistic depictions of mass shootings](https://www.pcgamer.com/ready-or-not-studio-says-planned-school-shooting-level-did-not-cause-split-with-publisher/), and an obsession with procedural realism, like evidence collection, to the point that it seems [“the \[developers\] forgot to add fun”](https://steamcommunity.com/id/tofucannibal/recommended/1144200/). In a scathing review, Kotaku characterized the game as [“an unsettling SWAT fantasy”](https://kotaku.com/controversial-steam-best-seller-ready-or-not-is-an-unse-1848317351). With the concept of games as an art form, it seems that social commentary on real-world issues isn’t something that games stray from, but has *Ready Or Not* gone too far?

The concept behind *Ready Or Not* is not a new one. Games like [SWAT](https://store.steampowered.com/app/560370/SWAT_3_Tactical_Game_of_the_Year_Edition/), and the popular [LSPDFR](https://www.lcpdfr.com/) mod for Grand Theft Auto have explored the idea of realistic representations of police procedure before. Where *Ready Or Not* diverges is just how realistic it aims to be, and the lengths that the developers have gone to to ensure realism. From the training level alone, the game’s use of detail is impressive.   

![][image1]  
*Pictured: The weapons in the training level are true training weapons that are used by police*

In the training level, the player is issued a training weapon based on the real-world [Glock 19T Gen 5](https://us.glock.com/en/pistols/g19-t-gen5-fs-us), notable for its blue color and specialized hybrid material slide designed for firing training rounds. Most games, like Counter Strike, or the Call Of Duty franchise, will not go further than simply giving the player the game’s standard sidearm. Void Interactive specifically researched, and then designed a training weapon true to what one would see in an interactive training scenario. 

The details continue into the missions. [CQB (close-quarters battle)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Close-quarters_battle) tactics are integral to the successful completion of missions. The game teaches you to be afraid of every entryway, every door could have an enemy lurking behind. As you take down enemies, the game requires that you clean up the situation, tagging civilians and evidence for the future investigation that the player never sees. 

![][image2]  
*Pictured: Successful collection of evidence after a completed mission*

The combat is intense, legitimately making the player afraid. The enemy AI is unpredictable, and you find yourself thrust into effectively randomized situations, with no idea where the enemies will be or what they will be doing. The pulsing background noise adds a sense of fear and urgency as you clear rooms. Unlike games that use exaggerated building proportions to facilitate better combat, everything is designed using realistic proportions, making clearing buildings a scary experience. All of these details come together to form the heart of *Ready Or Not*, unashamed realism. No real-world situation is too far of a line for the developers to cross. The missions depict the worst of what society has to offer, in a scarily objective way. 

*Ready Or Not* has no story, no overarching narrative that the player is reaching towards. You are playing a person with a job, and the missions are just that \- a job. There is no story tying things together, like Call of Duty. Each incident is its own individual story. People robbing a gas station, or a social media streamer taking hostages \- the incidents have no lasting impact beyond the mission. 

![][image3]  
*Pictured: A hostage is secured during a standoff at the 4-U Gas Station*

The lack of an overarching story, just a clear example of “good guys” vs. “bad guys” set against the backdrop of human evil makes us uncomfortable. Unlike movies and TV, there is no overarching conspiracy behind crime. Normal people do horrible things independently, and *Ready Or Not* captures this, and puts it on full display. We want to feel safe, we want to know that the people around us are good, and *Ready Or Not* does everything that it can to tear these ideas down. The game argues that these rare situations are an inevitable part of modern society, and that the only thing that can be done is to restore order. The game argues this using its own objectivity, creating a situation with no story, no narrative, just you, the innocent, and the evil- allowing you to come to your own conclusions based on the evidence that it presents to you. This idea hits close to home in a time plagued with unspeakable acts of violence- the presence of true evil in our society.

![][image4]  
*Pictured: A selection of posters in the game’s Headquarters level*

Whether you agree with the game’s arguments or not, the game sits as an interesting commentary on the presence and nature of evil. As all art should, the game forces us to confront potentially uncomfortable truths, a noble goal that more games should strive to replicate. Any other game, without the backdrop of evil would come across as goofy \- Team Fortress 2 with criminals, but *Ready Or Not* combines its underlying arguments with an unprecedented degree of realism in a way that creates a truly terrifying experience.
